Indonesian Students Association - The ASEAN Way: The next phase of regionalization in Southeast Asia Discussion Panel                  Indonesian Students Association - The ASEAN Way: The next phase of regionalization in Southeast Asia Discussion Panel   Occurs: 4/28/15 NYU Kimmel Center KC 914 ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) leaders look to conclude the ASEAN Economic Community in the coming months, deepening economic integration by bringing diverse economies into a com- mon market. But with the rising affluence and power of East Asian countries like China and India, ASEAN’s political unity will be further tested to conclude its code of conduct for the South China Sea later this year, an issue that has caused significant unrest in many ASEAN countries. Will ASEAN take this challenge as a an opportunity to share further political integration? Or will nationalist policies and vested interests across the myriad regime types fracture ASEAN’s credibility as a regional player? Join us for a timely discussion session with NYU ISA, SSA and the NY Southeast Asia Network. Moderator Margaret Scott, Adjunct Assistant Professor, NYU Wagner Speakers David Denoon, Department of Politics, New York University John Gershman, Wagner Graduate School of Public Service, New York University Ann Marie Murphy, School of Diplomacy and International Relations, Seton Hall University       Indonesian Students Association - The ASEAN Way: The next phase of regionalization in Southeast Asia Discussion Panel    Occurs: 4/28/15 NYU Kimmel Center KC 914 ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) leaders look to conclude the ASEAN Economic Community in the coming months, deepening economic integration by bringing diverse economies into a com- mon market. Indonesian Students Association - The ASEAN Way: The next phase of regionalization in Southeast Asia Discussion Panel                  Indonesian Students Association - The ASEAN Way: The next phase of regionalization in Southeast Asia Discussion Panel   Occurs: 4/28/15 NYU Kimmel Center KC 914 ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) leaders look to conclude the ASEAN Economic Community in the coming months, deepening economic integration by bringing diverse economies into a com- mon market. But with the rising affluence and power of East Asian countries like China and India, ASEAN’s political unity will be further tested to conclude its code of conduct for the South China Sea later this year, an issue that has caused significant unrest in many ASEAN countries. Will ASEAN take this challenge as a an opportunity to share further political integration? Or will nationalist policies and vested interests across the myriad regime types fracture ASEAN’s credibility as a regional player? Join us for a timely discussion session with NYU ISA, SSA and the NY Southeast Asia Network. Moderator Margaret Scott, Adjunct Assistant Professor, NYU Wagner Speakers David Denoon, Department of Politics, New York University John Gershman, Wagner Graduate School of Public Service, New York University Ann Marie Murphy, School of Diplomacy and International Relations, Seton Hall University       Indonesian Students Association - The ASEAN Way: The next phase of regionalization in Southeast Asia Discussion Panel    Occurs: 4/28/15 NYU Kimmel Center KC 914 ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) leaders look to conclude the ASEAN Economic Community in the coming months, deepening economic integration by bringing diverse economies into a com- mon market.
